         "id": "SECTION_local_content",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgGeo21\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgGeo21', '0%')\" src=\"\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: In this map, the continent is highlighted © Mapswire (<htcite0>)</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "dd4f3c8a-6624-4df5-93ac-37e0a4be9fdc",
                     "text": "Mapswire",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Our Coordinates</h3>Before pinpointing our location on Earth, let’s consider a question:</p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>>Reflection: Are we using the correct number of variables?</b><br /><br />Could we be oversimplifying by using only longitude (<b>θ</b>) and latitude (<b>δ</b>) to locate ourselves on the Earth's surface?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<h4>Simplification</h4>When we use only latitude and longitude to determine our location, we are indeed simplifying. This approach assumes a constant average Earth radius, estimated at 6,371 kilometers (Km) (or 6,371,000 meters (m))",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "fd003897-89a6-4d01-ae79-da9e564d9583",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "924f3991-5eec-4639-b307-5ce39447f6f6",
                     "text": "NASA",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "To better understand this simplification, let’s look at an example. By assuming a constant Earth radius, we don’t remove it from our calculations; rather, we omit it in the final representation of coordinates. This allows us to express the locations of cities like Tokyo and Montevideo with latitude and longitude alone",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1804b247-7fe8-4cff-a4e2-91accbaa936a",
                     "text": "Google Search",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "fb327056-722a-41e9-9f72-e1e77a5318c9",
                     "text": "Google Search",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul class=\"citation\"><li><b>Tokyo</b>: (35,6764° North, 139,6500° East)</li><li><b>Montevideo</b>: (34,9055° South, 56,1851° West)</li></ul></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<h4>All variables</h4>To express coordinates more precisely, it’s essential to use the same unit of measurement for all coordinates. On the Earth's surface, when we work with angles, we can simplify calculations by omitting the Earth’s radius. However, for three-dimensional accuracy, we need to include the radius and convert angle measurements from degrees to radians before continuing with calculations",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "fd003897-89a6-4d01-ae79-da9e564d9583",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul class=\"citation\"><li><math display=\"block\"><mn>θ'</mn> = <mn>θ</mn> <mfrac><mi>π</mi><mi>180</mi></mfrac></math></li><li><math display=\"block\"><mn>ϕ</mn> = (90 - δ) <mfrac><mi>π</mi><mi>180</mi></mfrac></math></li></ul><p>Next, we apply these converted angles in the formulas for spherical-to-Cartesian conversion, considering the radius <b>r</b>:</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center>(x, y, z) = (r cos(θ') sin(ϕ), r sin(θ') sin(ϕ) , r cos (ϕ))",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "fd003897-89a6-4d01-ae79-da9e564d9583",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ".</center>"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul class=\"citation\"><li><b>Tokyo</b>: (-3944126.27, 3350784.05, 3715609.67) </li><li><b>Montevideo</b>: (2907683.28, 4341002.95, -3645642.93)</li></ul></p><p>With this three-dimensional representation, we achieve a complete and highly precise location.</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
